The '''Marhanets train and bus collision''' occurred on 12 October 2010, at [[Marhanets]], [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]], [[Ukraine]] when a train collided with a passenger bus on a [[railroad crossing|railroad level crossing]]. Forty-three people were reported dead and nine injured.<ref name="Reuters"/> The bus driver, whose actions allegedly caused the collision, was killed in the accident as well.<ref name="Reuters"/> The collision was the worst single [[road accident]] in Ukraine's history by number of victims.<ref>{{cite web|title=Train crushes bus, leaving 41 dead in Ukraine's worst traffic accident|url=http://news.scotsman.com/world/Train-crushes-bus-leaving-41.6578250.jp|publisher=Scotsman.com|accessdate=12 October 2010|date=13 October 2010}}</ref>

== Accident ==
[[File:Map of Ukraine political simple Oblast Dnipropetrowsk.png|Dnipropetrovsk Oblast in Ukraine|thumb|left]]
The collision between a [[midibus]] carrying around 48 passengers and a [[locomotive]] occurred at 08:30 a.m. local time (05:30 UTC)<ref name="AFP"/> at an unmanned railway crossing.<ref name="Azarov: Government to allocate Hr 100,000 to each family of train-bus collision victims"/> Of those who were killed, 38 died at the scene and the others in hospitals from their injuries.<ref name="Reuters"/>

[[Ukrzaliznytsia]]'s press service reported that a preliminary theory on the cause of the accident was the violation of traffic rules by the driver of the bus.<ref name="Ukrzaliznytsia forms commission to investigate cause of bus-train accident"/>

== Reaction of the authorities ==
The [[Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine]] planned to allocate 100,000 [[Ukrainian hryvnia|hryvnias]] (approx. 12,600 US dollars) to each family of those killed and injured in a collision.<ref name="Azarov: Government to allocate Hr 100,000 to each family of train-bus collision victims">{{cite web|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/news/nation/detail/85972/|title=Azarov: Government to allocate Hr 100,000 to each family of train-bus collision victims|publisher=Kyiv Post|date=12 October 2010|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref> Officials said this was the deadliest vehicle accident in the country's history.<ref name="Forty-three killed in bus, train crash">[http://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/forty-three-killed-in-bus-train-crash/story-e6frfku0-1225937928211 Forty-three killed in bus, train crash]</ref> President [[Viktor Yanukovych]], on a visit to the region at the time, declared Wednesday the 13th a day of national mourning.<ref name="Reuters">{{cite web|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idAFTRE69B22420101012|title=Train and bus collide in Ukraine, 43 killed|publisher=Reuters Africa|date=12 October 2010|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref> Yanukovych also ordered for an investigation into the incident to be carried out in order to determine who bore responsibility for the crash<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11522009|title=Ukraine train and bus collision kills 42|publisher=BBC News Online|date=12 October 2010|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref> and instructed transport officials to install automated crossing gates at all railway crossings to prevent cars, buses and trucks from ignoring signals.<ref name="Forty-three killed in bus, train crash"/>

Road and railway accidents are common in Ukraine, where the roads are in poor condition, vehicles are poorly maintained, and drivers and passengers routinely disregard safety and traffic rules.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/40-killed-in-ukraine-train-collision-2104507.html 40 killed in Ukraine train collision]</ref>

